		 	<span id="comment_score_64231676" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64231676); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~upuv">upuv</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~upuv">( 1201447 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64231676">		
		on Sunday February 11, 2024 @07:43AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23222902&amp;cid=64231676">#64231676</a>)
		<small><a href="//slashdot.org/~upuv/journal/" title="Saturday May 02, 2009 @02:35AM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64231676"><p>For an org that has there **** together cloud is far cheaper.</p><p>On prem requires excess capacity already spun up.  On prem resources need far in advance planning.  On prem lacks burst capacity capabilities for the most part.  On prem also has an additional overhead of operations overheads to maintain, physical and the virtualisation platforms.</p><p>Now there are very valid reasons for on-prem kit.  Lots actually.  But for most organisations cloud solves huge volume of issues.</p><p>It falls apart when that org however forgets the cloud does require maintenance.  On-prem forces orgs to not forget about some level of maintenance.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64231676">
